import java.security.MessageDigest;

public class Main{
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            String text = "Hello World";

            MessageDigest md = MessageDigest.getInstance("MD5");
            byte[] digest = md.digest(text.getBytes());

            StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
            for (byte b : digest) {
                sb.append(String.format("%02x", b));
            }

            System.out.println("Text : " + text);
            System.out.println("MD5 Digest : " + sb.toString());
        }
        catch (Exception e) {
            System.out.println("Error: " + e);
        }
    }
}






1. Small Definition

MD5 (Message Digest Algorithm 5) is a cryptographic hash function that takes any input message and produces a 128-bit (32-hex character) hash value.
It is mainly used for integrity checking, not for security (because it is vulnerable to collisions).


---

2. Small Algorithm (Steps)

1. Pad the message so its length becomes 448 mod 512.


2. Append 64-bit length of the original message to make the total size a multiple of 512 bits.


3. Initialize 4 buffers: A, B, C, D (each 32-bit).


4. Divide message into 512-bit blocks.


5. For each block:

Break into 16 words (32-bit each).

Perform 64 operations using:

Non-linear functions (F, G, H, I)

Left shifts

Modular addition


Update A, B, C, D.



6. After processing all blocks, concatenate A, B, C, D to form the 128-bit MD5 hash.
